(Cite as: 1 A.K.Marsh. 401,  8 Ky. 401 (Ky.),  1818 WL 1437 (Ky.)) Court of Appeals of Kentucky. Long v. Carlyle. Dec. 2, 1818. *1 ON A WRIT OF ERROR TO REVERSE A JUDGMENT OF THE WOODFORD CIRCUIT COURT. West Headnotes Judgment 228 k 233 228 Judgment 228VI On Trial of Issues 228VI(B) Parties 228k233 k. Determination as to All Parties. Most Cited  Cases In a joint action against two, on a joint note, it is error to give judgment against one, while the suit is depending against the other. JUDGE OWSLEY DELIVERED THE OPINION OF THE COURT:FNa1 FNa1. Absent Judge Logan. This being a joint action brought against Long and Young upon a joint note, according to the repeated decisions of this court, it was irregular, whilst the cause was depending and undetermined as to Young, to enter a final judgment against Long. In a joint action against two, on a joint note, it is error to give judgment v. one, while the suit is depending v. the other. The judgment must, therefore, be reversed with cost, the cause remanded, and further proceedings had not inconsistent with this opinion. Ky.App. 1818. Long v. Carlyle 1 A.K.Marsh. 401, 8 Ky. 401, 1818 WL 1437 (Ky.) END OF DOCUMENT
